				</definition>
				
				<activity>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Meaningfully negate the following propositions (without just saying "It is not the case that...").
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li><m>e</m> is a negative real number.</li>
							<li>Iowa is the tenth largest state.</li>
							<li>17 is a prime number.</li>
						</ol>
						<solution>
							<ol>
								<li><m>e</m> is a nonnegative real number.</li>
								<li>Iowa is not the tenth largest state.</li>
								<li>17 is a composite number.</li>
							</ol>
	
	
						</solution>
	
	
	
					</statement>
	
				
				</activity>
	
				
				<exploration>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Determine the truth values of the following propositions.
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>Math 149 meets on Mondays and the capital of Iowa is Des Moines.</li>
							<li>Math 149 meets on Mondays and the capital of Minnesota is Minneapolis.</li>
							<li>Math 149 meets on Mondays or the capital of Minnesota is Minneapolis.</li>
						</ol>
						
	
					</statement>
					
					<solution>
						<p>We want to emphasize that the truth of the conjunction or disjunction depends <em>only on the truth of the constituent statements</em>. It doesn't matter whether it makes sense semantically to combine the constituents this way.</p>
						
						<ol>
							<li>This is true, as both constituents are true.</li>
							<li>This is false; the capital of Minnesota is St. Paul, not Minneapolis.</li>
							<li>This is true, since it's a disjunctive statement and one of the constituents is true (Math 149 meets on Mondays).</li>
						</ol>
	
					
					</solution>
	
	
	
				
				</exploration>
				
				
