				</definition>
				
				<exploration>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Determine the truth values of the following statements. Identify which row of <xref ref="table-implication" /> you are in.
						</p>
						<ol>
							<li>If <m>x</m> is negative, then <m>-5x</m> is positive.</li>
							<li>If we have Math 149 today, then it is Wednesday.</li>
							<li>If <m>9 > 5</m>, then dogs do not have wings.</li>
							<li>If <m>2=4</m>, then Calvin Coolidge is our greatest president.</li>
						</ol>
	
					</statement>
					<!-- 
	<solution>
						<p>As with conjunction and disjunction, there need be no causal relationship (or any relationship at all) between the constituents in an implication. To actually deduce the implication, however, usually does require a causal link to be established.</p>
						<ol>
							<li>This is true.</li>
						</ol>
	
					</solution>
	 -->
	
	
				</exploration>
	
	
				
				<p>
					The formalization of mathematical logic ramps up a bit when we consider conditional statements.
					It is important to remember that we define the truth value of the proposition <m>P \Rightarrow Q</m> <em>purely formally</em> based on the structure of the conditional statement and the truth values of the constituents <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.
					There need not be a causal relationship between <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>!
				</p>
				
				<p>
					The last two rows of <xref ref="table-implication" /> are also worth a moment of our time.
					They state that if the statement <m>P</m><fn>Often called the <em>antecedent.</em></fn> is false, then the <em>implication</em> <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is <em>true</em>.
					Note that this is different than saying that <m>Q</m><fn>Often called the <em>consequent.</em></fn> is true.
					When the implication <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is true because <m>P</m> is false, we usually say that <m>P\Rightarrow Q</m> is <term>vacuously true</term>.
				</p>
				
				<activity>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Suppose Dr. Janssen promises that, if everyone has solved their Rubik's Cube by Friday, then he will bring Defenders (on pretzel with everything) to class<fn>This is purely hypothetical.</fn>.
							Unfortunately, a few students do not solve the Cube by Friday, so Dr. Janssen does not bring Defenders.
						</p>
	
						<p>
							Determine the truth value of the implication "If everyone can solve their Cubes by Friday, Dr. Janssen will bring Defenders to class".
							How does this help you think about vacuous truth?
						</p>
						
						
	
	
					</statement>
	
				</activity>
				
