							<statement>
								<ol>
									<li>Assuming that the voter turnout in each state and DC is exactly 60.2% of citizens of voting age, and that each voter cast a vote for either Clinton or Trump, construct a scenario in which Trump could have won the election while receiving less than 25% of the nationwide popular vote.</li>
									<li>In your answer to the previous part, which states did you assume Trump would win? Why did you choose those states?</li>
									<li>If you wanted to construct a winning coalition of states for Trump that contained the smallest number of popular votes, should you include more larger states or more smaller states? Give a convincing argument to justify your answer.</li>
									<li>What assumptions did you make in order to construct your scenario for the first question? Were they reasonable? Why or why not?</li>
								</ol>
							</statement>
						</exploration>	

							
						</subsection>




						<subsection> 
							<title>If not the electoral college, then what?</title>
							
							<principle>
								<statement>
									Now that we've explored it a bit, how do you feel about the electoral college?
								</statement>
							</principle>
							
							
							<p>
								There are several proposed alternatives to the electoral college, including:
							</p>
							
							<ol>
								<li>Whoever wins the popular vote (with a plurality) wins.</li>
								<li>States could split their votes (like Maine and Nebraska already do).</li>
								<li>Proportional system: states could split their electoral votes based on the popular vote proportion earned in the state, so e.g., a candidate with 35.7% of the vote gets exactly 35.7% of the electors.</li>
							</ol>
							
							
							<exporation>
								<statement>
									<p>
										What do you think of the alternatives proposed above? What are their positive and negative features? Should one replace the electoral college? Or should we continue with things as they are?
									</p>
								</statement>
							</exporation>




							
							
							
						</subsection>



						
					
					
				</section>
				
				<section xml:id="Mar-10">
					<title>Mar. 10: Gerrymandering</title>
					
					<subsection>
						<title>Introduction and History</title>
					
					<p>
						Another idea closely linked to that of the electoral college and apportionment is <term>redistricting</term>: once a state has its apportionment for House seats following a census, it needs to draw district lines on its map to determine which geographic regions its House members will represent.
						This is known as a <term>district map</term> or <term>district plan</term>.
						However, the history of drawing lines on a map is fraught. This week, we'll take a look at some of the ways in which mathematics can help us describe or evaluate fairness.
					</p>
					
					<exploration>
						<statement>
							<p>
								In <xref ref="img-gerrymandering-intro" />, suppose each circle represents a voter, with the red circles representing Republicans and blue circles representing Democrats.
							</p>
							<figure xml:id="img-gerrymandering-intro">
							 <image width="45%" source="./images/gerrymandering_intro.png" />
							 <caption>A hypothetical population of voters.</caption>
							 </figure>

							 <ol>
							 	<li>If you had to divide the population into five congressional districts, each having an equal number of voters, how would you do it? Where would you draw the district boundaries?</li>
							 	<li>In the plan from your answer to the first question, how many districts would have a majority of Republican voters, and how many would have a majority of Democrats?</li>
							 	<li>Suppose you are a Republican who wants to make sure that your party has a majority in as many districts as possible. Where would you draw the district boundaries, and how many districts would your party control?</li>
							 	<li>Repeat the previous question, but this time assume you want to maximize the number of districts in which Democrats have a majority.</li>
							 	<li>What do you notice? What do you wonder?</li>
							 </ol>
				
						</statement>

					</exploration>
					
					<p>
						What we've just observed is an example of <term>gerrymandering</term>, the process of drawing district lines to give an advantage to a group of voters. Gerrymandering is named for Elbridge Gerry, the governor of Massachusetts in 1812, who helped draw state senate election districts to benefit his party.
						The Boston Weekly Messenger printed an editorial cartoon that drew the offending district as a dragon, dubbed the <q>Gerry-Mander</q> (see <xref ref="gerrymander" />).
					</p>
					<figure xml:id="gerrymander">
					<image width="45%" source="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/96/The_Gerry-Mander_Edit.png" />
					<caption>The mythical gerrymander</caption>
					</figure>

					
					<exploration>
						<statement>
							<p>
								In 2018, the data journalism website FiveThirtyEight launched the <url href="https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/redistricting-maps/">Atlas of Redistricting</url>, a helpful tool for looking at existing district plans and comparing them to possible new plans.
								Use their site to examine Iowa, your home state (if different), and 2-4 additional states. Do any of them seem to be gerrymandered? How are you deciding?
							</p>
							
						</statement>
					</exploration>
					
					
					</subsection>

					<subsection>
						<title>Techniques: Packing and Cracking</title>
						
						<p>
							Two techniques that are often used to gerrymander a district plan are known as <term>packing</term> and <term>cracking</term>.
							<em>Packing</em> refers to the notion of concentrating like-minded voters into a few non-competitive districts.
							<em>Cracking</em> refers to the practice of spreading like-minded voters out among multiple districts to dilute their influence.
						</p>
						
						<exploration>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Consider <xref ref="img-packing-cracking" />. In this district plan, Republicans earn 12 of 25 votes and win 4 of 5 seats. Explain how this plan uses packing and cracking to give Republicans an advantage.
								</p>
								<figure xml:id="img-packing-cracking">
									<image width="45%" source="./images/packing-cracking.png" />
									<caption>Packing and cracking</caption>
								</figure>
							</statement>
						</exploration>
						
						<question>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Devise a set of criteria that <em>you</em> think is fair and reasonable for a district plan. 
									Can you think of any instances in which gerrymandering might be desirable?
								</p>
							</statement>
						</question>



						
						
					</subsection>


					
					
				</section>
				
				<section xml:id="Mar-12">
					<title>Mar. 12: Rules for Redistricting</title>
					
					<p>
						Courts have generally held that the 14th Amendment requires congressional districts to have as close to equal populations as is practical.
						With a couple of exceptions via particular federal laws, most of the rules for drawing districts are up to the states.
						However, there are a few common requirements.
						</p>

				<assemblage>
					<title>Redistricting Rules</title>
					<p>
						<statement>
							<ul>
								<li>Contiguity: all parts of the district should be geographically connected.</li>
								<li>Compactness: residents in districts should live relatively close to one another (though measuring this is hard, as we'll see).</li>
								<li>Preserving political boundaries: districts should strive not to cut through cities, counties, or other municipal entities.</li>
								<li>Preserving communities of interest: when possible, districts should not separate groups of voters who live near one another and have common political, social, or economic interests.</li>
							</ul>
						</statement>
					</p>
				</assemblage>


				<exploration>
					<statement>
						<p>
							The laws in Idaho specify that <q>to the maximum extent possible, [redistricting plans] should avoid drawing districts that are oddly shaped</q>. Using this incredibly clear, unambiguous, helpful definition of compactness, put the districts in <xref ref="fig-districts" /> in order from <q>least oddly shaped</q> to <q>most oddly shaped</q>.
						</p>
						<figure xml:id="fig-districts">
							<caption>Some district shapes.</caption>
							<image width="45%" source="./images/districts.png" />
							</figure>
						
						
						</statement>
					</exploration>
					
					
					 <exploration>
					 	<statement>
					 		<p>
					 			Iowa considers compact districts to be those which are <q>square, rectangular, or hexagonal in shape, and not irregularly shaped, to the extent permitted by natural or political boundaries.</q> When comparing two redistricting plans, Iowa state law prescribes two specific measures of compactness: length-width compactness and perimeter compactness.
					 		</p>
							<ol>
								<li>Length-width compactness assumes a district is most compact when its length and width are equal. A district's compactness under this measure is the absolute value of the difference between its length and its width. Using this definition, order the districts in <xref ref="fig-districts" /> from most compact to least compact.</li>
								<li>Perimeter compactness assumes that the most compact districts are those with the shortest perimeter (i.e., the length of the boundary). Using <em>this</em> definition, order the districts in <xref ref="fig-districts" /> from most compact to least compact.
							</li>
						</ol>
						</statement>
					</exploration>
					
					<exploration>
						<statement>
							<p>
								In the state of Michigan, districts are required to be <q>as compact as possible, measured by drawing a circle around the district and assessing the area within the circle (and within the landmass of the state) but outside the district lines.</q> In other words, the tighter a circle can be made to fit around the district, and the more the district fills the circle, the more compact the district is.
								Using <em>this</em> definition of compactness, order the districts in <xref ref="fig-districts" /> from most to least compact.
							</p>
						</statement>
					</exploration>
					
					<p>
						As the previous three explorations suggest, the method for measuring compactness has a major influence on what we call compact.
					</p>

					<exploration>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Find a picture of the Fourth congressional district in Illinois.
								Give a sense for how you think this district would measure up under the previous three compactness metrics.
								Does this seem to be the result of a gerrymander?
								Then look into <em>why</em> the district was drawn this way.
							</p>
						</statement>
					</exploration>




							
					
					
				</section>
				
				
				
				
